or Social Ecology to provide media support to the U.S.\'s largest protests against genetic engineering and the corporate control of food at the USDA\'s Ministerial in Sacramento.  In October 2003, two of our trainers spent a week in Florida working with the Ruckus Society to train organizers opposing the November Free Trade Area of the Americas Ministerial meeting in Miami in messaging and mass-action design.  In November 2003 we returned to Florida to provide our communications, media strategy and video production skills to supporting the StopFTAA media team.\r\n<p>\r\nThe smartMeme project has also conducted numerous trainings and workshops for grassroots activists to effectively integrate media and organizing strategies.  Through our trainings and campaign work in eight different states, the smartMeme curriculum has touched thousands of activists and provided tools for re-thinking organizing and media strategies. \r\n<p>\r\nOur outreach and organizing efforts have mobilized tens of thousands of people, united diverse constituencies, and achieved international media coverage for issues ranging from opposition to the invasion of Iraq, to a rejection of corporate control and the dangers of genetic engineering.  \r\n<p>\r\nOur images have helped educate and inspire thousands of activists and consumers.  smartMeme strategy essays have appeared in numerous progressive publications and we have produced several compilations of our analysis and writing.\r\n<p>\r\nIn 2004 smartMeme has had the opportunity to continue working with diverse grassroots coalitions as facilitators, strategists, designers, and trainers.  We supported farmers’ struggles in Vermont with advertising, communications strategy and on the ground media support.  We’ve also facilitated a unique coalition of Native American tribes, commercial fisherman and environmentalists through a campaign planning and messaging process around environmental restoration issues in Northern California.\r\n','','2004-10-03 